<div class="bio" data-idx="7" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Claudia Jaguaribe</h2>
	<p>Claudia Jaguaribe is born in Rio de Janeiro. She lives and works in São Paulo. Since 1990 she has been taking part in exhibitions in major museums and galleries, in Brazil and abroad. She has a degree in Art History, Art and Photography, and her work is extremely representative of multifaceted practices and of the diversity of contemporary photography. Her production features aesthetic research that uses different media, such as photography, video, the Internet and installations, to grapple with different questions of today. As such, she works in a variety of formats and uses a variety of means of production, from studio photography to documental photographs, which she works on subsequently. 
	</p>
	<p>In the past nine years, she has turned to the question of landscape as a reinvention of nature in the series “When I Saw”, and in the series of urban landscapes such as “About São Paulo” and “Built Landscape - Among Hills”, about Rio de Janeiro. In 2010, “Built Landscape” was nominated to the Picted Photography Award and was included in the book Growth, edited by teNeus. Also during that year, Claudia received the Marc Ferrez Award for Photography from Funarte, for the project “Your way”. She has published ten books, and contributed to many other volumes with other artists.
	</p>
	<p>Her book Airport was selected to the edition Fotolivros latino-americanos, (Cosac Naify, 2011). Her works are part of the following collections: Inhotim – Instituto de Arte Contemporânea e Jardim Botânico, Brumadinho (MG); Museu de Arte Moderna de São Paulo (MAM-SP) (Museum of Modern Art) ; Pirelli Collection at the São Paulo Museum of Art (Masp-SP); Maison Européenne de La Photographie, Paris; Instituto Italo-Latino Americano (IILA), Rome; Itaú Cultural-sp, São Paulo; Instituto Figueiredo Ferraz, Ribeirão Preto (SP); as well as in private collections.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="8" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Claudio Edinger</h2>
	<p>Claudio Edinger is the award winning author of 14 photobooks and a novel called “The Paradox of Seeing”, scheduled for release in the Fall of 2014. 
	Born in Rio de Janeiro in 1952, he began teaching photography at Parson’s School of Design in 1979 and later, in 1992 at the International Center of Photography, both in New York. Since 2013, he teaches History of Contemporary Photography at Casa do Saber School, in São Paulo.
	</p>
	<p>His work is especially visible in Brazil in various Art collections such as the Museum of Art of São Paulo, Museum of Image and Sound (Brazil), Museum of Contemporary Art of São Paulo, Metropolitan Museum of Curitiba (Brazil), AT&T Photo Collection, Equity International Photo Collection, Brazil Golden Art Fund, Itaú Cultural (Brazil), Centro Cultural Banco do Brasil and in the most important private art collections of his country.
	</p>
	<p>Edinger received the Leica Medal of Excellence twice (1983 and 1985); the Hasselblad Award in 2012; The Higashikawa Award (Japan) in 1999; Life Magazine Award in 1989; The Ernst Haas Award in 1990; the JP Morgan Award (Brazil) in 1992; the Pictures of the Year Award in 1992; the Marc Ferrez Award (Brazil) in 2012; and the Brasil Porto Seguro Prize in 2007 and 2011.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="9" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Colin Dutton </h2>
	<p>Colin Dutton was born in London in 1966.
	After taking a degree in Documentary Photography at the University of Wales, Newport, Colin moved to Italy where has has lived since 2002.
	As a professional photographer, Colin works for editorial and commercial clients around Europe and North America. He also undertakes documentary projects for books and exhibitions and he gives talks and workshops on photography.
	</p>
	<p>He participated to those following exhibitions: Photofusion Gallery, London - Fusion Exhibition, 1991; St David’s Hall, Cardiff - Emerging Artists, 2001; Photofusion Gallery, London - Extracts, 2001; Spazio Paraggi Gallery, Treviso - Piccole Memorie dalla grande Guerra, 2008; Folkwang Museum, Essen - Teaching Photography, (curated by Paul Seawright), 2010; The Air Gallery, London - Lost in Landscape, 2011; Spazio Paraggi,Treviso - A Place To Sit, 2011; Spazio Paraggi,Treviso - Percorsi Sensibili, 2013.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="10" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Edu Simões</h2>
	<p>
	Edu Simões (São Paulo, 1956) started his career as a photojournalist, in 1976. Three years later he became one of the founding members of photo agency F4, where he remained until 1982, when he joined the team at IstoÉ magazine as assistant photo editor. In 1988, he began to work freelance and was photo editor at Goodyear magazine, where he remained until 1992. He published a series of photographic essays in the Cadernos de literatura brasileira (Notebooks of Brazilian Literature) at the Instituto Moreira Salles, in 1996. The following year, he became photo editor of the magazines Bravo and República. His project Gastronomia para um dia de trabalho duro (Gastronomy for a hard day’s work) was exhibited in 2011 at the FotoRio Festival and in the Maison Européenne de la Photographie, in Paris.
	</p>
	<p>He was awarded the Vladimir Herzog Prize for Human Rights, in 1980. His work forms part of the collections of the Pirelli/ São Paulo Assis Chateaubriand Museum of Art (Masp), São Paulo’s Modern Art Museum (MAM-SP), the São Paulo Pinacoteca do Estado Museum,
	the Sao Paulo Museum of Image and Sound (MIS), the Museum of Brazilian Art (MAB-Faap), the Maison Européenne de la Photographie and Consejo Mexicano de Fotografía. In June 2013, he presented the work I HAVE A DREAM, open air photography exhibition in Favela da Rocinha, in Rio de Janeiro - Brazil.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="11" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Erika Lafrennie</h2>
	<p>Erika Lafrennie is a traveler, writer, photographer, and nomad. She was born an old soul and began her illustrious travel career at age two when she pulled up a cardboard box-cum-airplane, climbed in, and never looked back. Erika Lafrennie has lived in and traveled to more than 27 countries across Europe, Africa, Asia, and the Middle East. She speaks several languages and holds a MA in Geopolitics. A self-taught photographer, Erika Lafrennie developed a love of blending photography with graphic design and mixed media. She recently left a career in the US Intelligence Community to pursue art full time.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="12" style="display: none;">
