</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="19" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Les Nivaux</h2>
	<p>Les Nivaux, couple of french artists, live and work closed to Paris, when they do not travel !
	Him, born in 1958, graduate of Louis Lumière School, Paris and University Paris VIII. Interested in conceptual photography and video art in the 80th, he is involved in photographic performances and exhibits photographic installations (L’Espace des Halles de Paris 1986 – Electra Musée d’Art Moderne 1984).
	</p>
	<p>Her, born in 1978, graduate of School art of Caen (DNAP & DNSEP).
	Together, they have exibited in Galerie du Centre Iris, Itinéraire photographique du Limousin, Manifesto in Toulouse…
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="20" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Lou Sarda</h2>
	<p>Her artistic touch and creative approach were further developed when she became an actress. She has been working for more than 10 years both for cinema and television, in her native France and abroad.
	</p>
	<p>Lou Sarda started photography following a film shoot in Tokyo. This experience quite literally “opened her eyes” and she described it as a “visual shock”. At this time, the urge of taking pictures became both obvious and a necessity.
	She began by photographing fellow artists: singers, actors or dancers. However, she rapidly decided to focus on women. Her photographs reveal a subtle understanding of her subjects, their body, their fragility, their grace, and their soul… Shooting after shooting, Lou Sarda wonders how to find her models’ “secret inner child”, and she strives to reveal their “wild female self”. Some describe her work as urban poetry, through raw and dreamlike, wild and mysterious images.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="21" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Lucas Lenci</h2>
	<p>Lucas was born in 1980 in São Paulo, where he lives and works.
	He studied Industrial Design and Photography at Belas Artes in São Paulo. He worked for 5 years as a producer in editorial and commercial projects for important photographers from different countries. In 2005, he spent some time in New York, an important period for his creative process.
	</p>
	<p>Lucas is the third generation of photographer of his family; his grandfather was an important name for more than 3 decades working as a photojournalism for the most important periodicals of his time. For this reason, Lucas also runs Instituto Peter Scheier, an organization dedicated to promote and preserve the memory of his family’s work.
	In 2011, he founded the first Brazilian on line gallery dedicated exclusively to photography. Fotospot, is an on-going project which helps Lucas to stay connected to the market and helps him in his creative process and in the creation of his series.
	Today with more than 15 exhibitions in different cities such as Madrid, Tokyo and São Paulo, his work is already part of important private collections and institutional archives.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="22" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Mahesh Shantaram</h2>
	<p>Mahesh Shantaram quit his day job in Washington DC in 2005 to pursue a diploma in photography at the Speos Institute, Paris. He has been an independent photographer ever since.
	</p>
	<p>Mahesh Shantaram’s primary interest lies in using personal and subjective documentary photography to study complex systems, societies, and institutions, particularly with reference to contemporary India. His most popular work, Matrimania, was seen at the Sony World Photography Awards 2011 (3rd Prize, Arts & Culture), Photoquai 2011, PhotoPhnomPenh 2012 (curated by Christian Caujolle), and nominated for Prix Pictet 2013 (‘Consumption’). 
	In the past couple of years, Mahesh Shantaram’s work has received international attention in magazines such as the New York Times, Financial Times, Sunday Times, Liberation, Le Monde, and The National.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="23" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Maria Pleshkova</h2>
	<p>Maria Pleshkova was born in 1986 in Moscow. She studied Photojournalism at Moscow State University and School of Visual Arts. Later, she attended the Eddie Adams Workshop in USA (2012) and International Summer School of Photography in Latvia (2014).
	</p>
	<p>Maria has won several international photography awards including China Press Photo Contest, Young Russian Photographers Contest, Prix de la Photographie (Paris), and became a finalist of the Inge Morath Award and the International Photography Awards. Her work was shown at several international festivals including Seville European Film Festival (Spain), Photography Open Salon (Arles, France), Circulation(s) Festival of young European photography (Paris, France), La Quatrième Image Photo Fair (Paris, France).
	Maria Pleshkova works on the border between art and documentary photography, bringing a deep and unique approach. In her work, Maria focuses on exploring people’s inner spaces.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="24" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Nafise Motlaq</h2>
	<p>Nafise Motlaq is an Iranian documentary photographer and journalism senior lecturer at Putra Malaysia University. She worked for newspapers in Iran before she moved to Malaysia in 2004 to continue her studies in PhD of Mass Communication. So far her photographs, multimedia, and video reportages have been published is numerous media and exhibited in several group exhibitions in Iran and overseas.
	</p>
	<p>Her first photo book titled «A Given Path» was published in Malaysia in 2010 and has been selected as best 50 titles for international rights. Her major interests in photography are women issues, interfaith dialogue and human rights.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="25" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Rogério Reis</h2>
	<p>Rogério Reis was born in 1954 and has been a photographer since 1977. He has worked for 17 years as a documentary photographer concentrating on the various aspects of the Rio de Janeiro Carnival: such as costumes criticizing politicians or the participation of the gay movement, as well as the innocence and frankness of the street groups found in the poorer outlying neighborhoods. This work gave way to several exhibitions and a book with the title «Na Lona» (On Canvas).
	</p>
	<p>He has had 25 solo exhibitions and has participated in 51 collective showings. Also, the character of the photographer in the Fernando Meirelles 2002 film “City of God” is based upon Rogério and his personal history.
	In 1999 he received the FUNARTE National Prize of Photography. His work is present in the following permanent collections: The Museu de Arto de Sao Paulo, the Museum of Modern Art in Rio de Janeiro, the Fogg Art Museum, the Danforth Museum of Art and The Maison Européenne de la Photographie in Paris.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="26" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Sheila Oliveira</h2>
	<p>She is born in 1968 in São Paulo (SP), where she currently lives. She has a degree in Librarianship and Documentationa and made several specialization courses in photography and visual arts. She is currently pursuing Post Graduation in Art Therapy.
	In 2002 she founded the Emporium Photographic studio specializing in food photography, whose work received the Abril Photojournalism Award Trophy and the Sao Paulo World Capital of Gastronomy.
	</p>
	<p>Her works have been exhibited in solo exhibitions: «Rastro visto de coisa só ouvida» Fauna Gallery, 2014; «Quase tão frágil» Coffee MuBE, 2013; «Flutuações», Gallery of the 12th Festival Winter of Bonito 2011 and «Raycuera», Cultural Center of the Central Bank of Brazil, in 1996.
	The artist received the Purchase “Casa do Olhar” Award at the 42nd and 39th Contemporary Art Exhibition Luiz Sacilotto and has works in the Museum UNESP, Bauru; Cultural Foundation of Beijing, China; among other institutions and private collections.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="27" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Steve Wells</h2>
	<p>Native to New Zealand, he became a founding member of the band Fur Patrol (Platinum disc and title # 1). At 27, he flew to Australia. 
	Genuine self-taught artist, he thrives on his experiences over his meetings and travels.
	</p>
	<p>Electronic engineer, he became a guitarist, he has naturally led to photography after receiving the old camera from his grandfather, himself a photographer in London in the 1920s. 
	In 2007 he moved to Paris as a photographer. 
	Full of crazy ideas, photography is just an excuse to can his surroundings.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="28" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Tiago Santana</h2>
	<p>Tiago Santana was born in 1966 in Crato, Brazil. 
	After studying mechanical engineering, he moved to the United States for one year and this is where he bought his first camera. Returning to Brazil, he participated in numerous photographers’ meetings, and thus deepened his knowledge of Brazilian photography. 
	He has been working as a professional photographer since 1989. In 1992, his work on the pilgrimages of Juazeiro do Norte, which is a symbol city of religiosity in Brazil, has drawn the attention on him.
	</p>
	<p>With two other photographers, he founded in 1994 Tempo Imagem, a publishing and photographic archives house that specialises in the publishing of photo books. 
	In 2000, he published his first book, Benditos, followed in 2003 by Brasil Sem Fronteiras. 
	He was awarded Best Brazilian photographer of the year during three consecutive years (2007, 2008 and 2009), and received the Porto Seguro Brasil Prize in 2010 with the photo essay A Luz Perpetua eo Resplendor. 
	Tiago Santana has participated in important exhibitions in Brazil, as well as in the United States, Germany, Japan, Cambodia and Russia. He has works in major photographic collections in Brazil and outside Brazil.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="29" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Tsutomu Yamagata</h2>
	<p>Tsutomu Yamagata is a documentary photographer based in Tokyo. He was born and raised in Tokyo, majored in Law at Law department, Keio University. He worked at the Business Planning Department of an energy industry. At the same time, he was gradually attracted and involving himself in photography, and finally quit his job to dedicate himself to photography. He learned photography through self-education, and started giving exhibitions actively. In 2012, he published a photo book, “Thirteen Orphans”, gave exhibitions in Japan and overseas, including TOKYO PHOTO and a solo exhibition at Colorado Photographic Arts Center. In 2013, he attended Review Santa Fe, was selected to Photolucida’s Critical Mass Top 50, and received the prize of Lens culture Portrait Awards.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="30" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Valérie Chauffour</h2>
	<p>Born in France in 1963, Valerie lives in Paris. She became interested in photography when she was 19. Over the years of diligent practice, landscapes and faces, moods and colors fed her. Her job as an airline pilot, who took her around the world, and her taste for art, gave her the opportunity to refine her eyes. 
	To benefit from the experience and encouragement from great photographers like Eric Bouvet or Françoise Huguier been very rewarding for her. The same is true for technical training she was able to attend at Central Saint Martin’s College in London.
	</p>
	<p>Not wishing to be locked in a particular style, she experiments based on her feelings and desires, different themes and approaches. 
	La Quatrième Image is her first exhibition.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="31" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Vincent Lecomte</h2>
	<p>Vincent Lecomte is a freelance photographer specialized in portrait and chiaroscuro. Fascinated by the people who live away from the world, he tries to capture what unites us despite the distance. His work has been shown in Brazil, Canada, England and the United States. In Paris, he has exhibited at Palais du Luxembourg, Cité des Sciences and Museum d’Histoire Naturelle. He participated to the eighteenth International Biennial of the Image (Nancy). His photographs were published at Le Seuil editions, in Le Nouvel Observateur, in Mozi Magazine (US). He collaborated to the movies ‘Oceans’ by Jacques Perrin.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="32" style="display: none;">
	<h2>William Gaye</h2>
	<p>Trained at the ENS Louis Lumière (graduated in 2008), William Gaye explores photography in its many dimensions and confronts them in a move involving constantly the choice of a position. The artistic impulse that drives his projects is illustrated by the diversity of its work (itinerant projects, participatory, collage, panoramic images from different media, etc.) that question our relationship to the images and what they can make visible or not. Thus, each project or meeting is an opportunity to find a new way to experience the process of creating and restoring images created based on a given subject and a given environment.
	</p>
</div>
<div class="bio" data-idx="33" style="display: none;">
	<h2>Yvon Buchmann</h2>
	<p>A passion, a true autodidact - Yvon Buchmann dedicates a true passion for photography for his six years old, when his father placed in his hands his first camera. Passion that will stand the test of time. A true autodidact, Yvon Buchmann has continued to study the work of the great French and American photographers to understand their technical sophistication and refinement of their mode of expression. He is fascinated by the atmosphere of peace and carelessness that existed during the years after the war and fixed by Doisneau, Ronis, Boubat Kertez, Brassaï, and of course Henri Cartier-Bresson.
	</p>
	<p>For Yvon Buchmann, photograph is capturing fleeting moments, capture a unique moment, show atmospheres, people’s feelings. His style at once pure and very subtle, because of his love of life and the human being, Yvon Buchmann expressed with great simplicity and poetry the sheer of daily life.
	</p>
</div>
